-- Pakistani stocks close higher; rupee strengthens, o/n rates flat
-- 
-- Thu Dec 04, 2014 07:39AM EST
-- None



KARACHI, Dec 4 (Reuters) - Pakistani stocks ended higher on Thursday, with the benchmark 100-share index of the Karachi Stock Exchange <.KSE> closing up 0.68 percent, or 218.20 points, at 32,090.93.

Investors were buoyed by rising foreign exchange reserves following comments by the finance minister that the International Monetary Fund would release another tranche of loans, and after a successful issue of five-year Sukuk bonds worth $1 billion, said Samar Iqbal, a dealer at Topline Securities. There are also indications Pakistan's turbulent political situation may stablise as opposition leader Imran Khan mulls calling off a planned nationwide strike if the government agrees to talks.